---
/**
 * advanced-ai-systems/0001 · Figure 2 — "Single agent vs multi-agent" (Module 1).
 *
 * Copied VERBATIM from docs/advanced-ai-systems/lessons/0001-multi-agent-systems-
 * when-and-when-not.html. Uses the shared arrowhead marker #arwR defined by <Fig0>.
 * Kept as an .astro component (not inline MDX) for reliable raw-SVG rendering.
 * SVG anchor ids (r2b) match the source DOM + the #s3 footnote.
 */
---

<figure>
    <svg
        viewBox="0 0 640 250"
        role="img"
        aria-label="A single agent keeps all state in one context window; a multi-agent system splits work across agents that must pass messages, adding coordination overhead."
    >
        <text x="320" y="18" text-anchor="middle" font-size="12" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >Single agent vs multi-agent</text
        >

        <!-- single agent -->
        <rect
            x="30"
            y="34"
            width="270"
            height="180"
            rx="10"
            fill="#e9f3ec"
            stroke="#2f5d3a"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="165" y="54" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >Single agent (the default)</text
        >
        <rect x="70" y="70" width="190" height="40" rx="6" fill="#ffffff" stroke="#2f5d3a"></rect>
        <text x="165" y="88" text-anchor="middle" font-size="9" font-weight="700" fill="#111110"
            >one LLM + tools</text
        >
        <text x="165" y="101" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >observe &rarr; think &rarr; act, in a loop</text
        >
        <rect x="70" y="122" width="190" height="34" rx="6" fill="#ffffff" stroke="#2f5d3a"></rect>
        <text x="165" y="143" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >ALL state in one context window</text
        >
        <text x="165" y="182" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" font-weight="700" fill="#2f5d3a"
            >no handoff loss · one place to debug</text
        >
        <text x="165" y="198" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >cheaper, lower-latency</text
        >

        <!-- multi-agent -->
        <rect
            x="340"
            y="34"
            width="270"
            height="180"
            rx="10"
            fill="#f6eef7"
            stroke="#b5179e"
            stroke-width="1.5"></rect>
        <text x="475" y="54" text-anchor="middle" font-size="10.5" font-weight="700" fill="#b5179e"
            >Multi-agent (a scaling pattern)</text
        >
        <rect x="360" y="70" width="78" height="34" rx="6" fill="#ffffff" stroke="#b5179e"></rect>
        <text x="399" y="91" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#111110">agent A</text>
        <rect x="446" y="70" width="78" height="34" rx="6" fill="#ffffff" stroke="#b5179e"></rect>
        <text x="485" y="91" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#111110">agent B</text>
        <rect x="532" y="70" width="58" height="34" rx="6" fill="#ffffff" stroke="#b5179e"></rect>
        <text x="561" y="91" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#111110">agent C</text>
        <line x1="438" y1="104" x2="475" y2="124" stroke="#9a2417" marker-end="url(#arwR)"></line>
        <line x1="485" y1="104" x2="475" y2="124" stroke="#9a2417" marker-end="url(#arwR)"></line>
        <line x1="561" y1="104" x2="490" y2="124" stroke="#9a2417" marker-end="url(#arwR)"></line>
        <rect x="380" y="126" width="190" height="30" rx="6" fill="#ffffff" stroke="#b5179e"></rect>
        <text x="475" y="145" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" fill="#111110"
            >message-passing / shared state</text
        >
        <text x="475" y="182" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8.5" font-weight="700" fill="#9a2417"
            >throughput on parallel work</text
        >
        <text x="475" y="198" text-anchor="middle" font-size="8" fill="#6b675f"
            >+ coordination tax (tokens, latency, failures)</text
        >
    </svg>
    <figcaption>
        A single agent holds everything in one window — no fragmentation, one debugger. Splitting
        into agents buys parallelism but trades in-context reasoning for <em>message-passing</em>,
        which is where the cost and the failure modes live.<sup><a href="#s3" id="r2b">2</a></sup>
    </figcaption>
</figure>
